04429nam a22005535i 9780804783460DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047834607 a10.1515/97808047834602doi  a(DE-B1597)564517  a(OCoLC)1198930537  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHQ247.A5K68 2012 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a306.740952/09045a306.740952/09045a306.740952090451 aKovner, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOccupying Power :bSex Workers and Servicemen in Postwar Japan /cSarah Kovner. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA note on names and nomenclature -- tIntroduction: A special business -- tOne. "To transship th em to some suitable island": making policy in the midst of chaos -- tTwo. Violence, commerce, marriage -- tThree. When flesh glittered: selling sex in Sasebo and Tokyo -- tFour. Legislating women: the push for a prostitution prevention law -- tFive. The high politics of base pleasures: regulating morality for the postwar era -- tSix. The presence of the past: controversies over sex work since 1956 -- tConclusion. Beyond victimhood -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe year was 1945. Hundreds of thousands of Allied troops poured into war-torn Japan and spread throughout the country. The effect of this influx on the local population did not lessen in the years following the war's end. In fact, the presence of foreign servicemen also heightened the visibility of certain others, particularly panpan-streetwalkers-who were objects of their desire. Occupying Power shows how intimate histories and international relations are interconnected in ways scholars have only begun to explore. Sex workers who catered to servicemen were integral to the postwar economic recovery, yet they were nonetheless blamed for increases in venereal disease and charged with diluting the Japanese race by producing mixed-race offspring. In 1956, Japan passed its first national law against prostitution, which produced an unanticipated effect. By ending a centuries-old tradition of sex work regulation, it made sex workers less visible and more vulnerable. This probing history reveals an important but underexplored aspect of the Japanese occupation and its effect on gender and society. It shifts the terms of debate on a number of controversies, including Japan's history of forced sexual slavery, rape accusations against U.S. servicemen, opposition to U.S. overseas bases, and sexual trafficking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aProstitutesxLegal status, laws, etc.zJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aProstitutionzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex-oriented businesseszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804783460zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804783460423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804783460.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles